 "modules": [
  {
   "title": "Module 1 · Basic Definitions",
   "html": "<p>Probability of an event $E$:</p>$$P(E) = \\dfrac{n(E)}{n(S)}$$<p>where $S$ is the sample space. Always $0 \\le P(E) \\le 1$. $P(\\text{not }E) = 1 - P(E)$.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "A fair die is thrown. Find P(getting a 4).",
     "a": "$P = 1/6$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 2 · Laws of Probability",
   "html": "<p><b>Addition law:</b> $P(A\\cup B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A\\cap B)$. If $A,B$ are <b>mutually exclusive</b>: $P(A\\cup B) = P(A) + P(B)$.</p><p><b>Multiplication law:</b> If $A,B$ are <b>independent</b>: $P(A\\cap B) = P(A)P(B)$. If dependent: $P(A\\cap B) = P(A)P(B|A)$.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "A card is drawn from a pack. Find P(King or Queen).",
     "a": "$P = 4/52 + 4/52 = 8/52 = 2/13$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 3 · Tree Diagrams",
   "html": "<p>Branches represent each possible outcome; multiply along branches, add between branches.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "A bag contains 3 red and 5 blue balls. Two balls are drawn without replacement. Find P(both red).",
     "a": "$P = \\dfrac{3}{8}\\times \\dfrac{2}{7} = \\dfrac{6}{56} = \\dfrac{3}{28}$."
    }
   ]
  }
